00:45:02.810 --> 00:45:04.720
What about immigration?

00:45:04.720 --> 00:45:07.370
Well, immigration,
actually, the framework

00:45:07.370 --> 00:45:10.940
is very much the same.

00:45:10.940 --> 00:45:15.650
If there are people who can
contribute to our society

00:45:15.650 --> 00:45:19.410
by coming here, then
we are better off

00:45:19.410 --> 00:45:24.035
by letting them in by the
same logic of specialization

00:45:24.035 --> 00:45:26.210
and comparative advantage.

00:45:26.210 --> 00:45:27.300
If there are people--

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:31.070
for example, let's say US folks
don't want to pick our crops,

00:45:31.070 --> 00:45:33.223
and we don't want
to clean toilets.

00:45:33.223 --> 00:45:35.390
But picking crops and
cleaning toilets at a low wage

00:45:35.390 --> 00:45:38.300
is a terrific opportunity for
someone from another country.

00:45:38.300 --> 00:45:41.860
Then we could be better
off by letting them in.

00:45:41.860 --> 00:45:43.390
Or let's say-- as
it's turned out

00:45:43.390 --> 00:45:46.210
to be true historically-- the
kind of person who wants take

00:45:46.210 --> 00:45:49.330
the risk to immigrate to America
is the kind of person who

00:45:49.330 --> 00:45:51.667
often becomes an entrepreneur
and thinks up new ideas.

00:45:51.667 --> 00:45:53.500
Much of the entrepreneurial
ideas in America

00:45:53.500 --> 00:45:55.660
have come from our nation's
history of immigrants.

00:45:55.660 --> 00:45:57.100
Because who picks up and leaves?

00:45:57.100 --> 00:45:58.850
It's kind of a
risky thing to do.

00:45:58.850 --> 00:46:00.475
To pick up, leave
your home, and leave,

00:46:00.475 --> 00:46:01.840
and come to this unknown place.

00:46:01.840 --> 00:46:03.550
And those risk-loving
people are often

00:46:03.550 --> 00:46:06.110
the kind of people
who think up new ideas

00:46:06.110 --> 00:46:08.160
and want to start
new businesses.

00:46:08.160 --> 00:46:10.550
So for that reason,
immigration has traditionally

00:46:10.550 --> 00:46:13.530
been an enormous benefit
to the US economy.

00:46:13.530 --> 00:46:15.890
And I think today, the general
consensus-- this is more

00:46:15.890 --> 00:46:17.630
controversial than free trade.

00:46:17.630 --> 00:46:20.390
But I think the general
consensus among economists

00:46:20.390 --> 00:46:23.510
is that immigration on net
is good for the country,

00:46:23.510 --> 00:46:26.860
but there's redistributional
consequences.

00:46:26.860 --> 00:46:29.890
It's good for rich
people because they

00:46:29.890 --> 00:46:33.375
get low-pay people to pick their
fruits and do their lawn work.

00:46:33.375 --> 00:46:35.500
But it's bad for people
who used to pick the fruits

00:46:35.500 --> 00:46:37.350
and do the lawn work.

00:46:37.350 --> 00:46:39.480
So once again, if
we can figure out

00:46:39.480 --> 00:46:42.030
a way to compensate
the losers, immigration

00:46:42.030 --> 00:46:43.860
is probably [INAUDIBLE] good.

00:46:43.860 --> 00:46:45.210
Now, it's more complicated.

00:46:45.210 --> 00:46:48.848
When we import a car, it doesn't
get welfare or commit crimes.

00:46:48.848 --> 00:46:50.890
Immigrants might get on
welfare or commit crimes,

00:46:50.890 --> 00:46:53.430
so it's more complicated
than just free trade.

00:46:53.430 --> 00:46:55.560
So what you have to
do in that case is you

00:46:55.560 --> 00:46:58.140
have to look at the evidence.

00:46:58.140 --> 00:47:01.110
And the evidence is that
immigrants commit crime

00:47:01.110 --> 00:47:04.710
at a much lower rate than
comparable US citizens

00:47:04.710 --> 00:47:08.070
and collect welfare at a much
lower rate than comparable US

00:47:08.070 --> 00:47:09.000
citizens.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:10.667
So you can't compare
an immigrant to me.

00:47:10.667 --> 00:47:13.250
An immigrant is more likely to
commit crime or collect welfare

00:47:13.250 --> 00:47:15.920
than I am, but immigrant's
also less educated than I am.

00:47:15.920 --> 00:47:17.170
I'm not the comparable person.

00:47:17.170 --> 00:47:18.780
Compare an immigrant
to the person

00:47:18.780 --> 00:47:20.920
they're replacing
in the labor market.

00:47:20.920 --> 00:47:23.025
A low-skilled US citizen.

00:47:23.025 --> 00:47:24.900
Immigrants are less
likely to collect welfare

00:47:24.900 --> 00:47:28.030
and less likely to commit
crimes than are those people.

00:47:28.030 --> 00:47:31.080
So as a result, those arguments
don't really bode well

00:47:31.080 --> 00:47:32.670
for restricting immigration.

00:47:32.670 --> 00:47:34.300
On the other hand,
I think there's

00:47:34.300 --> 00:47:36.300
very few people who say
we should have a totally

00:47:36.300 --> 00:47:39.330
porous and open border.

00:47:39.330 --> 00:47:41.040
Because of illegal
movement of goods,

00:47:41.040 --> 00:47:44.615
and because we don't want
people objectively criminal

00:47:44.615 --> 00:47:46.490
in other countries that
are also risk-loving,

00:47:46.490 --> 00:47:48.670
we don't necessarily
want them here.

00:47:48.670 --> 00:47:50.218
So I think this is a hard issue.

00:47:50.218 --> 00:47:51.593
Unlike international
trade, where

00:47:51.593 --> 00:47:54.410
I think economists would
say just more is good,

00:47:54.410 --> 00:47:57.410
I think that immigration, there
are some difficult trade-offs,

00:47:57.410 --> 00:47:59.630
because people come
with a set of baggage

00:47:59.630 --> 00:48:02.450
that goods don't come with.

00:48:02.450 --> 00:48:04.060
But I think economists
would generally

00:48:04.060 --> 00:48:06.310
say a lot of the
same arguments apply.

00:48:06.310 --> 00:48:09.100
We might need a more
comprehensive policy

00:48:09.100 --> 00:48:11.700
than we have when it
comes to trading goods.